  "market_context": "NQ1! 3-minute chart on Fri 27 Jun '25 around 00:30–02:30. Messy bullish price action following a candle 2 closure that engulfed prior candles, with ES showing SMT (already swept the low) validating long setups while NQ consolidated.",
  "key_observation": "By blending candle closures with the phases of price (expansion, retracement, consolidation, reversal), each protected swing can be trailed forward until expansion is met with opposing expansion — signalling reversal and that the protected low becomes the new draw on liquidity.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify a candle 2 closure engulfing prior candles, confirming change in state of delivery and price trading higher.",
    "Validate the long bias despite an unswept consolidation low by referencing ES, which already took out the correlated low — an SMT divergence.",
    "Mark the initial protected swing from the change in state of delivery, then trail it forward to a new protected swing as a fresh opposing candle forms.",
    "Observe expansion through a high, then watch the next candle: it closes back inside the previous candle's body rather than the range, signalling continuation higher and a new protected swing.",
    "Note a small consolidation distrusted because price could dip into the fair value gap; acknowledge the trade might be missed, but expansion follows anyway.",
    "Recognise expansion → retracement into fair value gap → expansion as the clean continuation signature.",
    "When another consolidation forms, anticipate a sweep of the low to continue higher; price aggressively sweeps the low, closes back over the level, forming a new protected low.",
    "After further expansion above highs, observe the next move is not a retracement or consolidation — it is expansion met with expansion, defining a reversal.",
    "Conclude the protected low is no longer safe and becomes the draw on liquidity; price subsequently trades down to take that low out."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reversed after expansion met with opposing expansion and traded back down to sweep the previously protected low, as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "Trending price action is rarely clean; by tagging each phase (expansion/retracement/consolidation) and trailing protected swings, the trader anticipates the next phase. When expansion meets expansion, the trend's last protected swing flips into the draw on liquidity.",
